{{Infobox Artwork | image_file=Pieter Bruegel the Elder - The Fall of the Rebel Angels - RMFAB 584 (derivative work).jpg | title=The Fall of the Rebel Angels | artist=[[Pieter Bruegel the Elder]] | year=1562<ref>dated and signed "<small>M.D.LXI BRVEGEL</small>"</ref> | type=[[Oil painting|Oil]] on panel | height_metric=117 | width_metric=162 | metric_unit=cm | imperial_unit=in | city=[[Brussels]] | museum=[[Royal Museums of Fine Arts of Belgium]] }} '''''The Fall of the Rebel Angels''''' is an oil-on-panel by [[Dutch and Flemish Renaissance painting|the Netherlandish Renaissance]] artist [[Pieter Bruegel the Elder]], painted in 1562. It is currently held and exhibited at the [[Royal Museums of Fine Arts of Belgium]] in [[Brussels]].
==Description== Painted in 1562, Bruegel's depiction of this subject is taken from a passage from the [[Book of Revelation]] (12, 2-9)<ref>[http://www.biblegateway.com/passage/?search=Revelation+12&version=KJV King James Version, 12, 2-9]</ref> and reveals the artist's profound debt to [[Hieronymous Bosch]], especially in the grotesque figures of the fallen angels, shown as half-human, half-animal monsters. Together with ''[[Dull Gret|Dulle Griet]]'' and ''[[The Triumph of Death]]'', which have similar dimensions, it was probably painted for the same collector and destined to become part of a series.<ref>Cf. Pietro Allegretti. ''Brueghel''. Milan:Skira, 2003. {{ISBN|0-00-001088-X}} {{it}}</ref>
The composition with a central figure placed among many smaller figures was favoured by Bruegel at this time, not only in other paintings such as ''Dulle Griet'', but also in the series of engravings of the Vices and the Virtues which he had just completed for the [[Antwerp]] publisher [[Hieronymous Cock]].<ref>Compare Bruegel's engravings ''[[:Commons:File:Pieter Bruegel the Elder - Superbia (Pride) - WGA3539.jpg|Pride]]'' and ''[[:Commons:File:Pieter Bruegel the Elder - Gula (Gluttony) - WGA3541.jpg|Gluttony]]''.</ref> The [[archangel]] [[Michael (archangel)|Michael]] and his angels are shown by Bruegel in the act of driving the rebel angels from Heaven. [[Pride]] was the sin which caused the fall of [[Lucifer]] and his companions, and the conflict of good and evil, vice and virtue, is a theme which recurs constantly in Bruegel's work.<ref>Max Seidel, Roger H. Marijnissen. ''Bruegel''. Pt.2, Random House, 1985.
{{ISBN|0-517-44772-X}}</ref>
==Gallery of details== <gallery widths="200px" heights="200px" perrow="4" caption="Details"> File:Pieter Bruegel I-Fall of rebel Angels IMG 1458.JPG|A good angel File:Pieter Bruegel I-Fall of rebel Angels IMG 1446.JPG|The fallen angels File:Pieter Bruegel I-Fall of rebel Angels IMG 1455.JPG|Fighting the rebels
